TITLE: Japan becomes the fifth country to reach the moon after its spacecraft landed on the lunar surface
SUMMARY: The unmanned Japanese spacecraft SLIM landed on the moon this weekend, marking a first for the East Asian nation, but problems with its solar panels appear to imperil the mission.

TITLE: EU chief says Israel was responsible for Hamas' surge to power in Gaza: 'Financed by the government'
SUMMARY: During a speech in Spain, the European Union’s foreign policy chief Josep Borrell said Israel was responsible for financing Hamas and their surge to power in Gaza.

TITLE: Biden's Iran nuclear containment policy failing as UN warns regime has enough material for 'several' warheads
SUMMARY: The International Atomic Energy Agency chief Rafael Grossi has repeatedly complained about Iran's lack of transparency over the past year and the difficulty trying to obtain compliance.

TITLE: Russian forces bring down Ukrainian drone, munitions explode and set Klintsy oil depot ablaze
SUMMARY: Russian military forces brought down a Ukrainian military drone over an oil depot in the town of Klintsy, causing it to release its munitions and set the area ablaze.

TITLE: Poland's new government praised by European Union for efforts to restore rule of law
SUMMARY: The European Union Commissioner for Justice, Didier Reynders, applauded Poland's new pro-EU government on Friday for its efforts to restore the rule of law.

TITLE: Netanyahu rejects Palestinian state in postwar scenario, prompting criticism from the US
SUMMARY: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu rejected calls for a Palestinian state after his country defeats Hamas in Gaza. He also suggested the war could continue for several months.

TITLE: German lawmakers approve plan to loosen citizenship rules in effort to attract skilled workers
SUMMARY: German lawmakers have approved legislation that eases rules on gaining citizenship and ends restrictions on holding dual citizenship, according to officials.

TITLE: Activists in Norway  charged after blocking entrances to government offices to protest wind farm impact
SUMMARY: A group of protesters are facing charges for allegedly blocking government offices to protest a wind farm in central Norway's Fosen district, officials say.

TITLE: Suspects charged in torture, murder of Hmong American comedian in Colombia
SUMMARY: Minnesota-based Hmong American comedian and activist Tou Ger Xiong was allegedly tortured and held for ransom before being murdered in the city of Medellín, Colombia.

TITLE: La Kena, notorious Mexican cartel leader, captured; group accused of killing 2 US tourists
SUMMARY: A Mexican drug cartel leader whose faction is alleged to have kidnapped four U.S. tourists, killing two of them, was arrested with his associates in shopping mall on Friday

TITLE: Thailand rescue workers retrieve remains of 23 victims following fatal factory explosion
SUMMARY: Rescue workers carried out the task of recovering the remains of the 23 victims of a fireworks factory explosion in central Thailand on Thursday, officials say.

TITLE: Measles outbreak: UK declares national health incident over rising cases
SUMMARY: Health officials in the United Kingdom are warning that low rates of uptake for the measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccine is leading to outbreaks across the country.

TITLE: North Korea sentences 2 teens to 12 years of hard labor for watching K-pop: report
SUMMARY: North Korean authorities sentenced the two 16-year-old girls to 12 years of hard labor after they were previously convicted of watching K-pop, which is music from South Korea.

TITLE: Philippines landslide kills 10, including 5 children, officials say
SUMMARY: Heavy rains in the southern Philippines triggered a landslide that buried a house, killing at least 10 people on Friday. The landslide occurred in a remote mountain village.

TITLE: South Korea urges UN council to break silence on North Korea's escalating missile threats
SUMMARY: South Korea urged the U.N. Security Council to address North Korea's escalating missile tests and threats during an emergency closed meeting on Thursday.

TITLE: NATO to hold largest military exercises in decades, involving around 90,000 personnel
SUMMARY: NATO is set to launch its largest military exercises in decades involving around 90,000 personnel. The drills aim to demonstrate NATO's capability to defend its territory up.

TITLE: Sri Lanka drug crackdown leads to more than 40,000 arrests, drawing criticism from UN
SUMMARY: Sri Lankan authorities have conducted a crackdown on drugs, resulting in the arrest of over 40,000 people. The operation has drawn criticism from the United Nations.

TITLE: North Korea claims it tested nuclear-capable underwater drone capable of destroying naval vessels and ports
SUMMARY: North Korea's Defense Ministry claims it successfully tested a nuclear-capable underwater drone capable of destroying naval vessels and ports as it looks to keep bolstering its arsenal.

TITLE: Netanyahu says two-thirds of Hamas' fighting forces have been eliminated
SUMMARY: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu says up to 17 out of Hamas’ 24 fighting regiments have been taken out in combat inside the Gaza Strip.

TITLE: Gangs in Haiti have attacked a community for 4 days and residents fear the violence could spread
SUMMARY: Gang members are on a rampage in a large neighborhood in Port-au-Prince: Solino, which is home to many police officers. Residents fear the carnage could spread throughout the city.

TITLE: Unrest continues in Comoros after president's controversial reelection win
SUMMARY: Riots and unrest continued Thursday in the Indian Ocean island nation of Comoros, following President Azali Assoumani's contentious reelection.

TITLE: Slovene government to set up temporary migrant facilities at Croatian border
SUMMARY: Slovenia will establish temporary migrant handling facilities at the Croatian border, the central European nation's government announced Thursday.

TITLE: Donkey cart explosion kills Kenyan police officer, injures 4 others
SUMMARY: A Kenyan police officer was killed and four others were wounded after a suspected IED explosion blew up a donkey cart at the country's Somali border.

TITLE: Ex-leader's son renounces French nationality to run for president of Senegal
SUMMARY: Former Senegalese President Abdoulaye Wade's son, Karim, has renounced his French nationality so he can legally seek the office once held by his father.

TITLE: US ambassador to Russia visits imprisoned Wall Street Journal reporter Evan Gershkovich
SUMMARY: Lynn Tracy, U.S. ambassador to the Russian Federation, visited detained Wall Street Journal reporter Evan Gershkovich in Lefortovo Prison in Moscow.
